\begin_layout Standard
Consumers-oriented EEG headsets usually conceal signal processing behind
 proprietary algorithms, with little scientific evidence on what is truly
 measured.
 While building a tailored EEG helmet, we took the upper hand on the whole
 pipeline.
 With access to raw EEG signals, we looked into the literature to match
 the inner state we wanted to measure with actual neurological markers.
 We have used the following features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Vigilance: appoints for the ability to maintain attention over time.
 We use the ratio between beta frequency band (15-20Hz) and theta + low
 alpha frequency band (4-10Hz) for all electrodes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Oken2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Workload: increases with the amount of mental effort required to complete
 a task.
 We use the ratio between delta + theta band (1-8Hz) in near frontal cortex
 (F7, FP1, F8, T8) and wide alpha band (8-14Hz) in parietal + occipital
 cortex (P8, P7, O2, O1) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Antonenko2010,Schober1995"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Meditation: we used instantaneous phase locking value between front (FP1,
 F7, F8) and rear (O1, P7, P8) parts of the brain in alpha + beta bands
 (7-28Hz) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frey2014"

\end_inset

 -- mindfulness and body focus practices decrease the synchronization while
 transcendental practice increases it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Valence: designates the hedonic tone of an emotion and varies from positive
 to negative (e.g., 
\emph on
frustrated
\emph default
 vs 
\emph on
pleasant
\emph default
).
 We use the ratio between the EEG signal power in the left (F7, P7, O1)
 and right (F8, P8, O2) cortex in the alpha band (8-12Hz) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Molina2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Arousal: relates to the intensity of an emotion and varies from calm to
 excited (e.g., 
\emph on
satisfied
\emph default
 vs 
\emph on
happy
\emph default
).
 We use the EDA readings.
\end_layout

